               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18771022-767-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-767-18771022 t18771022-767-offence-1 t18771022-767-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18771022-767-charge-3" targOrder="Y" targets="def3-767-18771022 t18771022-767-offence-1 t18771022-767-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>767. <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <persName id="def1-767-18771022" type="defendantName">
                        <interp inst="def1-767-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def1-767-18771022" type="surname" value="TILKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def1-767-18771022" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE TILKE</persName>,<persName id="def2-767-18771022" type="defendantName">
                        <interp inst="def2-767-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def2-767-18771022" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="def2-767-18771022" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp> CHARLES BROOKS</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <persName id="def3-767-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-767-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-767-18771022" type="surname" value="PRIOR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-767-18771022" type="given" value="FREDERICK JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FREDERICK JOHN PRIOR</hi>
                  </persName>, Unlawfully<rs id="t18771022-767-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18771022-767-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18771022-767-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> conspiring by false pretences to cheat and defraud the Metropolitan District Railway Company.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. MONTAGU WILLIAMS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CHARLES MATHEWS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution; and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PURCELL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-143" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-143" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-143" type="surname" value="SOAK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-143" type="given" value="WILLIAM EDWARD"></interp>WILLIAM EDWARD SOAK</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 5, Wyndham Villas, Acton, and am assistant clerk in the accountant's office of the Metropolitan District Railway at Westminster—I am thoroughly conversant with the practice as regards issuing tickets on the Metropolitan Railway—the ticket col<lb></lb>lectors are stationed at each of the stations for the purpose of collecting tickets, which it is their duty to put into a bag provided for the purpose, and return the bag by train at distances of three to four hours to the ticket department, Blackfriars—trains of the Metropolitan Railway run on the Metropolitan District Railway, and trains of the London and North-Western Railway—the tickets are sorted into stations at the chief ticket office, Blackfriars, and checked by the returns from the stations, in order to see that they are properly accounted for—they are kept for three weeks, after which it is the practice to destroy them—the practice is the same with the Metropolitan tickets—the practice is different with regard to the mixed tickets issued by the Great Western Railway and the London and North-Western Railway—in the case of the latter it is the practice, after having examined them at our office, to forward them to the Railway Clearance House month by month—with the Great Western it is also the same practice, with a few exceptions, those exceptions being tickets issued from Addison Road, Uxbridge Road, Latimer Road, Notting Hill, Westbourne Park, and Bishop's Road, which tickets are dealt with in the same way as those of the Metropolitan and Metropolitan District tickets.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-144" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-144" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-144" type="surname" value="FINCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-144" type="given" value="CHARLES HENRY"></interp>CHARLES HENRY FINCH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a ticket examiner stationed at Gloucester Road station, employed jointly by the Metropolitan and Metropolitan District Railway Companies—in the course of my duties my attention was called to Tilke at the end of June at the Gloucester Road station, and I consequently watched him day by day—I have a book in which I entered the times at which I saw him, and the places, day by day—he was travelling by the Metropolitan Railway—it would be within my duty to examine the ticket with which he was travelling—I have the book (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—I have an entry in his</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220033"></xptr>
               <p>of the 30th June, when Tilke arrived at Gloucester Road with a second-class ticket from Uxbridge Road, by the 9.50 a.m. train—it was a Hammersmith train, and would not stop at Uxbridge Road; it goes a different way—on July 3rd he arrived by the 9.31 North-Western train with a ticket from Uxbridge Road to South Kensington—that stops at Uxbridge Road—I am not sure whether it was a return ticket—on the same day he returned by the 9.55 train with a half ticket from Sloane Square to Hammer<lb></lb>smith—it was the forward half—he delivered it up at the station—he travelled third class—the fare between Gloucester Road and Earl's Court is, single ticket, 1 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and return 2 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—the third single from Sloane Square to Hammersmith is 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., return 4 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I did not see Tilke any more on the 3rd—the next date is the 5th July, when he arrived by the 11.50 train from West Kensington (late North End) to Gloucester Road—I am not sure what ticket he had—he returned by the 12.17 with a forward half from Victoria to Earl's Court, getting into a train again at Gloucester Road—the fare between Victoria and Earl's Court is single 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and return 4 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—the next occasion was the 6th July, when he arrived at Gloucester Road by the 11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. London and North-Western train, giving up a ticket from Uxbridge Road to Gloucester Road, a forward half, and returned by the 11.38, forward half, from Charing Cross to Earl's Court—the fare between those stations and is 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. single, and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. return—on the 7th July he arrived by the 10.17, with" a proper ticket that day, and returned by the 11.4 Sloane Square to Earl's Court, backward half—the next occasion was July 9th, when he arrived by the 10.50—he had no ticket, and I charged him the third-class fare from Earl's Court, 1 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I next saw him on the 10th, by the 11.50 North End to Gloucester Road, Hammersmith train, which was the right one—he returned with an ordinary parliamentary ticket from Gloucester Road to Earl's Court—the next occasion was July 11th, when I saw him get out of a second-class carriage, walk up the platform into a third, and go on towards the Mansion House—on the 12th he came by the 11.50 with a Hammersmith ticket to Gloucester Road, forward half—he did not use the return half that day—it would be only available for one day—on the 13th I saw him arrive with a single ticket from Westbourne Park to South Kensington, by a London and North-Western train—those trains do not call at West-bourne Park—the fare is the same between Westbourne Park and Gloucester Road as between Westbourne Park and South Kensington, id. single and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. return—on the 14th July he arrived at 10.8, by the Richmond train, with the first or forward half of a return ticket from Uxbridge Road to Gloucester Road—the Richmond trains neither pass through nor stop at Uxbridge Road—he returned at 10.25 with a single ticket from Gloucester Road to Earl's Court, so that he did not use the second or backward half of the ticket he had used early in the day—the same day he arrived a second time at Gloucester Road with a single ticket from South Kensington to Earl's Court at 12.45, which ticket was cancelled at South Kensington—he was travelling towards Earl's Court—on the 17th July he arrived at Gloucester Road by the 12.17 train with a proper single ticket—I saw him return that day at 12.47, and he came down the ordinary exit staircase—he did not go to the booking office; he could not get to it that way—he passed straight to the platform without showing his ticket to any inspector—I did not see what ticket he had in his possession at that time—on the 18th July I saw him arrive by</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220034"></xptr>
               <p>the 12.1 train with the first half of a ticket from Uxbridge Road to Gloucester Road—the return half he didn't use that day—on the 19th July he arrived by the 11.47 Groat Western train, with the first half of a return ticket from Hammersmith to Gloucester Road—the Great Western trains do not pass through or stop at Hammersmith—at 12.3 he returned with a ticket from South Kensington to West Kensington—he entered the train at Gloucester Road, and did not use on that day the return half of the ticket he had used in the morning from Hammersmith to Gloucester Road—the third-class fare from South Kensington to West Kensington is 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. single and 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. return—the third return from Hammersmith to Gloucester Road is 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. single—going to the 24th July, he arrived at 9 47 a.m. at Gloucester Road, by a Great Western train, with the first half of a return ticket, Hammersmith to Gloucester Road, which ticket was cancelled at Hammersmith—he was not seen to use the return half—the same day he arrived at Gloucester Road by the 11.29 Hammer<lb></lb>smith train with the forward half of a return ticket, Hammersmith to Gloucester Road, cancelled at Hammersmith—I am not sure whether he used the return half—he returned that day by the 12.34—on the 25th July he arrived at Gloucester Road by the 10.38 a.m. Richmond train, with the first half of a return ticket from Kentish Town to Gloucester Road—the Richmond trains do not start from Kentish Town, and the return half he did not use—the third-class fare would be, return 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., single 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—on the 28th July he returned by the 11.10 train, Gloucester Road to Earl's Court, backward half, cancelled, not having used the first half—he did not arrive that day—during the entire month of July, down to the 11th August, I continued to watch him, during which time he was generally travelling with tickets which passed beyond the stations at which he alighted—he never returned with the corresponding half of the tickets, but with tickets taken at a station before that at which he entered the train.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I am ticket-examiner at the Gloucester Road station—my hours are from 8 a.m. till 8 a.m.—I go off an hour to dinner—I occasionally hand over my work to some one to assist me—I am supposed to only receive half the trains throughout the day—the Richmond trains do not pass Kentish Town, but it would be possible for a person to get out, and for some purpose of his own take the next train that came up, that train having come from another quarter—he would not be allowed to go out of the intermediate station—he might have come from Kentish Town though he arrived at Gloucester Road in the Richmond train—that could happen at Earl's Court and at the branch stations, but not on the main line from South Kensington to the Mansion House—Richmond trains go to the Mansion House, and he could arrive there though he came from the Edgware Road—it is possible to take a ticket at Kentish Town and travel up to Earl's Court, and then get into another train and arrive at Gloucester Road, not Uxbridge Road—it is not a privilege at some stations to come in by the exit door—it depends on circumstances whether a passenger can say, "I am coming back presently," and not be required to give up his ticket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> The rules and directions are that no passenger is to go away from the station without delivering up his ticket, and that is universally followed—I find it very seldom that a person alights at any station and waits for the next train.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220035"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-145" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-145" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-145" type="surname" value="BLYTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-145" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BLYTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a ticket-collector at Gloucester Road, in the service of the Metropolitan District Railway Company, and was on duty on the 17th July last, when my attention was called to Tilke, who entered the station by the usual exit and passed direct to the platform without showing his ticket to a collector—I followed him on to the Hammersmith platform, and asked to see his ticket, which he showed me—it was a return half from Sloane Square to Earl's Court already cancelled—it should be cancelled at Sloane Square, that is snipping it—the wrong half might be cut by mistake—I cannot say what it would convey to my mind—I ex<lb></lb>amined his ticket and gave it to him back—when I went back I made a com<lb></lb>munication to Osborne—Finch had drawn my attention to him—on the 30th I again saw Tilke at Gloucester Road, when he arrived by the 11.38 train with the first half of a return ticket from Hammersmith to Gloucester Road—I did not see the return half of the. ticket on that day—on the 31st July he arrived by the 1.1 North-Western train, and gave me a ticket from Hammersmith to Gloucester Road, first half—I did not see him use the return half—on the 30th August something similar happened—I have seen him frequently at Gloucester Road, and have had my attention called to irregularities connected with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I have seen him at the station in his butcher's clothes—the clipper may in a hurry clip the <hi rend="italic">wrong</hi> half of a ticket—it does not happen very often.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-146" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-146" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-146" type="surname" value="OSBORNE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-146" type="given" value="JAMES HICKS"></interp>JAMES HICKS OSBORNE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am inquiry inspector in the service of the Metropolitan District Railway Company—on the 17th July from informa tion that came to me I watched Tilke, who is employed by Mr. Scarlett, a butcher, of the Earl's Court Road, from his master's shop about 12.5—he was carrying some meat in a butcher's tray—when he arrived at Earl's Court Brooks was the collector on duty—Tilke went up to him and put his tray down on the desk alongside of him, and entered into conversation with him—I could not hear what was said, but I was sufficiently near to see Brooks and to be seen by him—I am known to Brooks—I saw him look towards me, and make signs with his eyes to Tilke, and saw his lips moving, though I could not hear what was said—Tilke became confused directly, and rushed from Brooks towards where I was standing, passed me, and went to the urinal—I could see a small paper parcel in one of his hands as he passed me—he first went inside the door of the urinal, but was not there long enough for any necessary purpose, and returned again immediately, again going past me, still carrying the parcel—the tray had in the meantime remained on the table—he again went to Brooks and passed him, and went outside the station out of my sight for Half a minute, or perhaps a minute, and returned again—I could not see the parcel then—he had had some private conversation with Brooks—from there he went to the booking-office and threw down a penny and asked for a ticket to Gloucester Road—the ordinary fare is 1 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>., but the parliamentary 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he passed on to the platform with that ticket, and I followed him—I saw him get into the train, and I got into the same—I travelled to Gloucester Road and got out, and saw him do so—I followed him—he passed out of the station, giving up the ticket he had taken at Earl's Court—he went to a house in Queen's Gate and delivered some meat there and returned—I still followed him to the Gloucester Road station—he entered by the exit without going to the booking-office or passing any ticket-collector, and went straight on to the Hammersmith plat<lb></lb>form</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220036"></xptr>
               <p>—I spoke to Blyth, who had spoken to Kim, he told me—Blyth made a communication to me—Tilke went by the next train, and I went by the same—we alighted at Earl's Court, and I followed him upstairs—Brooks was still the collector—Tilke appeared to give him a ticket in the ordinary way—it would be the ordinary duty of Brooks to collect a ticket from a passenger going away—he should allow no one to pass without—Gloucester Road is next to Earl's Court—a person going east, finding himself at Earl's Court, might get out there—tickets are fre<lb></lb>quently given up short of their destination.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> A great many passengers take tickets to places to which they do not actually go—they may have appointments made, and get out at particular platforms, and those cases may happen—the paper parcel Tilke had may have been meat—I don't think he knew me; he knew Brooks—he walked sharply; people usually do walk sharply at railway stations—Earl's Court Gardens is close to the railway station—when Tilke went out of the station with the paper parcel he was not away long enough to go to Earl's Court Gardens—he was gone long enough to get rid of the parcel.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-147" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-147" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-147" type="surname" value="PATTERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-147" type="given" value="JAMES JOHN"></interp>JAMES JOHN PATTERSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 32, Palace Road, Lambeth, and am a pensioned police sergeant—in July I was employed by the prosecuting company, and on the 19th I watched Tilke and saw him leave his employer's shop at about 11am. and go to Earl's Court—he carried a basket in his hand, in which there was a paper parcel—Brooks was acting as collector at the station—I saw Tilke put his basket down near where Brooks was standing—I remained at the door and watched them—neither of them knew me—I saw Tilke go from Brooks to the urinal, and come out in a short time and return to where his basket was—I then passed into the station and asked for a ticket for Gloucester Road—while standing at the ticket office people were intervening between me and the defen<lb></lb>dants Tilke and Brooks, so that I could not see exactly what passed, but I saw a mutual morion of the arms as though something was passing from one to the other—Tilke left the station—I passed on to the platform to Brooks with my ticket to examine and nip, and went to Gloucester Road and remained there on the platform—by the next train arriving at Gloucester Road Tilke came and gave something, presumably a ticket, to examiner Finch—I followed him to a house in Queen's Gate, and re<lb></lb>turned after him to Gloucester Road—when nearly opposite the station he took a green ticket from his pocket and looked at it—he then went into the station at Gloucester Road and gave a ticket to Finch, who nipped it and allowed him to go on the platform—he took no ticket at the book<lb></lb>ing office of either station, I am certain—he came by the following train—I am certain on the return journey he took no ticket at Gloucester Road—I thought the green ticket was a return ticket—I saw one of the edges was rough—I got into the train which he did, which took us back to Earl's Court—I followed him up the steps and saw him give up a ticket and leave the station—on the 20th July I again watched him. when he left his master's shop with his basket as before and went to Earl's Court station—Brooks was again the collector—he again placed his basket on the table and he and Brooks leant over it—I then saw Brooks standing a little way off' him—he had a leathern bag in his hand such as ticket collectors use for putting collected tickets into—he took some out, looked at them, and returned them—Brooks looked up</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220037"></xptr>
               <p>and saw me watching him and put down the bag and went to the head of the stairs—Tilke was then standing at the door—I went by the train and waited at the Gloucester Road station some time and saw him come and go to a house in Queen's Gate—then I gave up watching for that day—on the 24th July I again watched him and saw him leave the same place with the same basket and go to the same station—Prior was on duty at that time—Tilke held his basket under his arm when he got to the station—he went near to Prior, and Prior gave him a ticket or tickets—I was standing at the window of the booking-office some few paces off and saw the tickets pass—to the best of my belief there were two tickets—they might have spoken, but I was too far off to hear what they said—Tilke passed to the platform without going to the booking-office to get a ticket—I followed him down and went in the same train as he did to Gloucester Road, where he appeared to give up a ticket—he passed something to a collector—I followed him to the house in Queen's Gate, but saw him no more that day—on the 26th July I again watched him—Prior was on duty, and Tilke passed direct to the platform without taking a ticket, and at Gloucester Road he gave up what was presumably a ticket which I had never seen him take—I watched him to Queen's Gate and he returned to Gloucester Road—he passed to the Hammersmith platform without going to the booking office—he travelled back to Earl's Court and gave up a ticket—neither going nor returning did he take a ticket—on the 27th July I again we watched him, and exactly the same thing occurred—Prior was collector that day—on the 28th July he was again collector—Tilke arrived at the Earl's Court station—I saw Prior go to his ticket table and remove a newspaper, under which there were two tickets—he removed one and took it to Tilke on the platform without going to the booking office—I went to Gloucester Road with the object of watching Tilke again—he did not get out at Gloucester Road that day, but I believe went on to South Kensington—I watched him return from the direction of Queen's Gate—he went to Gloucester Road, I following him—I don't know whether be showed a ticket at Earl's Court—he made a motion to Prior—at Gloucester Road he showed a ticket to Finch and passed on to the platform without going to the booking office—I watched him back to Earl's Court—I fol<lb></lb>lowed him from the station to a public-house, where he remained a few minutes, and left—directly he had left Prior arrived and went into the public-house, and after a short time came and looked out of the door as though looking for some one—he then went in and remained.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> When I watched Tilke I went to the place of business, Mr. Scarlett's—I never lost sight of him—his taking a ticket was the exception—I don't recollect any other occasion than I have given—on that occasion I saw him speaking to Brooks, and then he left the station—I went in the train and he followed by the next—he might have taken a ticket in the interval, and if so it would be necessary for him to take one on his return journey—sometimes there is a good deal of traffic at Earl's Court, and sometimes it is quite clear—he could not have obtained a ticket except on the one occasion without my seeing him—I have seen him carrying meat in the ordinary course of business and deliver it at the house in Queen's Gate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I was instructed to watch.</p>
               <p>
